      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "In a global business setting, wearing traditional local clothing can actually command more respect and demonstrate a deeper understanding of the local culture. In many non-Western cultures, wearing traditional attire is seen as a sign of respect, humility, and a willingness to learn and adapt.\n\nWearing tailored Western attire in a non-Western setting can sometimes be seen as trying too hard to fit in or as a sign of cultural insensitivity. For example, wearing a suit and tie in a traditional Thai or Indian setting can be seen as out of place and may draw attention away from the business at hand.\n\nThat being said, it's not always necessary to abandon Western attire entirely. A well-tailored, modest outfit that incorporates some local elements, such as a traditional tie or pocket square, can be a good compromise. However, it's generally best to err on the side of caution and observe local customs and dress codes before the meeting.\n\nIn many cases, the most sophisticated approach is to blend in with the local culture without trying too hard. This can be achieved by learning a few key phrases in the local language, observing local customs and traditions, and dressing in a way that is respectful and understated. Ultimately, the key to sophistication is to be genuine,",
